Section 7			Yarrow
			(Achillea millefolium)

			By Howie M. Thomason RNCP
				hmt@ican.net
			      1-888-770-0033

	Read about Howie Thomason on our Meet the Team
	page; http://www.Life-Choices.com/team.html
----------

This month we will look at Yarrow.  It combines well with 
Boneset, the herb we looked at last month, for influenza 
and the common cold.


Common names;

Yarrow, Milfoil, Nosebleed, Thousand Leaf, Soldiers Woundwort.


Collection;

Yarrow should be gathered when it is flowering, usually 
between June and September. It is a perineal herb found 
throughout North America and Europe. It is often found 
on the roadside and waste lands.  The beautiful aroma
from this plant is one method of identification. Here in 
Ontario, I find it in sandy soil in fields.


Parts Used;

Some herbalists will say only the aerial parts can be used. 
Others will say the whole plant including the roots can be 
used.


Properties;

Diaphoretic		(sweating herb)
Hypotensive      	(reduce elevated blood pressure, 
			 tending to normalize systolic
                      & diastolic levels.)
Astringent;          (contract tissue by precipitating proteins)
Diuretic;            (increase secretion and elimination of urine)
Antiseptic;          (Destroys and prevents the development of 
			 microbes)
Carminative;    	(Stimulates peristalsis, relax stomach)


Constituents;

Up to 0.5% volatile oils, flavonoids, tannins, bitter alkoids.


Energy and Flavours;

Warm, Bitter, Spicy.


Indications;

Yarrow is one of our best diaphoretic herbs.  It is easily found 
and is a standard remedy for helping the body to deal with fevers. 
The hot infusion will raise the heat of the body, equalize the 
circulation and produce perspiration. It is very effective in 
fevers in children and adults. It has also been useful in measles 
and all of the eruptive conditions, especially where the eruption
is slow making its appearance. It can stimulate digestion and tone 
the blood vessels. It is considered a specific herb for conditions 
associated with high blood pressure. It can be used as a urinary 
antiseptic for infections such as cystitis.

Used externally it will aid in the healing of wounds.

It may be considered for amenorrhea, menorrhagia, and leucorrhea,  
all being caused, at least in part, by poor pelvic circulation and 
weakness.

This herb has long been associated with the battlefield and is a
specific antihemorrhagic wound remedy.  It can be used internally 
or externally for any condition of acute bleeding, especially from 
cuts and abrasions. It got its name from the warrior Achilles.


Combinations;

For fever it will combine well with Elder Flower, Peppermint, 
Boneset, Cyanne and Ginger.

For Raised Blood Pressure it can be used with Hawthorn, Lime 
Blossom and Mistletoe.


Preparation and Dosage;

Infusion: pour a cup of boiling water onto l-2 teaspoonfuls of 
the dried herb and leave to infuse for l0-l5 minutes. This should 
be drunk hot three times a day. When feverish it should be drunk 
hourly until sweating is produced.

Tincture: take 2-4ml of the tincture three times a day.
For those that do not want or like the alcohol in the tincture 
they can drop the tincture into a cup of hot water to evaporate 
the alcohol.

-----
References;

Dominion Herbal College Text
David Hoffmann, The New Holistic Herbal. 1990
Michael Tierra, The Way of Herbs. 1998

